1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:17,820
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa

2
00:00:18,525 --> 00:00:36,854
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:36,895 --> 00:00:41,021
The word I'd like to look at this evening is the word sila.

4
00:00:41,743 --> 00:00:44,246
So it's S-I-L-A.

5
00:00:45,509 --> 00:00:55,042
translates as morality, ethical behavior, that sort of thing.

6
00:00:55,063 --> 00:00:58,908
And it always comes first in the teachings.

7
00:01:00,229 --> 00:01:02,192
It's always sila-samadhi-panya.

8
00:01:02,213 --> 00:01:06,018
It's always ethical behavior, concentration, and then wisdom.

9
00:01:07,319 --> 00:01:09,963
And to understand that...

10
00:01:11,614 --> 00:01:16,503
I have to go back to the beginnings as to why unethical behavior happens.

11
00:01:18,525 --> 00:01:22,052
And it goes back to that point where we make a mistake.

12
00:01:22,632 --> 00:01:35,653
And this mistake of who we are, or what we are, manifests in a relationship of attachment to the world, or better, seeking happiness in the world.

13
00:01:35,713 --> 00:01:38,718
That's how the Buddha would put it, seeking happiness here and there.

14
00:01:41,078 --> 00:01:48,385
And that sort of relationship creates that sort of conflict.

15
00:01:48,546 --> 00:01:54,031
So we're always trying to manipulate the world and other people to make ourselves happy.

16
00:01:55,253 --> 00:01:58,275
And if they don't, we tend to want to just get rid of them.

17
00:02:00,799 --> 00:02:08,266
So you can see how from that basic mechanism, it's very easy to begin to behave in a way which is harmful.

18
00:02:09,580 --> 00:02:13,586
And that would be the definition of something which is not ethical.

19
00:02:14,286 --> 00:02:18,733
If it does harm to others or to ourselves, then it's unethical.

20
00:02:19,913 --> 00:02:30,147
And the five precepts, that's how we translate it, but the actual word sikarpada is a path of training.

21
00:02:31,890 --> 00:02:34,473
They're not actually commandments as such.

22
00:02:35,455 --> 00:02:37,258
It's when you realize that

23
00:02:38,032 --> 00:02:42,362
Now, ethical behavior is a measure of our delusion or wisdom.

24
00:02:43,346 --> 00:02:51,366
You realize that when you start at the basis of your behavior, then that's actually where your training is.

25
00:02:52,391 --> 00:03:03,069
So take something, the first one that we take, which is pretty straightforward, not to harm or kill any living being.

26
00:03:04,372 --> 00:03:06,094
So we start there.

27
00:03:06,475 --> 00:03:08,359
I think most of us have probably given that up.

28
00:03:10,093 --> 00:03:23,176
But then there's a more subtle way of harming living beings in perhaps ways that we weren't particularly aware of, like not putting food out for the birds in the midwinter.

29
00:03:23,897 --> 00:03:33,334
There's all sorts of little ways where our lack of communion, our lack of...

30
00:03:33,313 --> 00:03:36,998
What's the word?

31
00:03:38,502 --> 00:03:39,783
Oh good, I've lost it.

32
00:03:40,764 --> 00:03:41,186
What do we call it?

33
00:03:41,225 --> 00:03:42,026
Interconnectedness.

34
00:03:42,247 --> 00:03:47,275
Our lack of interconnectedness manifests in ourselves as callousness.

35
00:03:47,594 --> 00:03:57,550
So it becomes very fine, and then once we begin to see where that is, then the thing begins to flip.

36
00:03:57,530 --> 00:04:05,739
And just as we might have been cruel towards animals, etc., that moves over towards compassion.

37
00:04:07,901 --> 00:04:19,334
Just as we were perhaps once thieving from banks and things like that, and then not sharing things with people, see, it moves towards generosity.

38
00:04:20,535 --> 00:04:20,634
Okay?

39
00:04:21,036 --> 00:04:30,733
So all these things, like not being truthful, even to the slight point of exaggeration, he moves towards truthfulness.

40
00:04:31,473 --> 00:04:39,127
So it's not as though you move towards a place which is not ethical, you move towards the more positive places.

41
00:04:39,687 --> 00:04:44,495
Now that movement doesn't come without wisdom, and that's the important thing to realize.

42
00:04:45,353 --> 00:04:56,269
So the approach to our happiness, to our ultimate happiness, has to have this sort of two-pronged approach.

43
00:04:57,312 --> 00:05:03,661
It's not only the growth of wisdom, it's not only the growth of understanding, but the change in behavior.

44
00:05:03,882 --> 00:05:05,985
So the whole thing has to be systemic.

45
00:05:07,487 --> 00:05:09,471
And that's what Seeler is pointing to.

46
00:05:10,074 --> 00:05:12,579
And it's there, of course, within the Eightfold Path.

47
00:05:12,819 --> 00:05:18,146
So, with the right understanding, there's a change in the heart.

48
00:05:18,165 --> 00:05:23,533
And that's the second of the path, the right attitude.

49
00:05:23,553 --> 00:05:27,779
From that is right speech, right action, and eventually change.

50
00:05:27,759 --> 00:05:28,701
Right livelihood.

51
00:05:29,362 --> 00:05:31,526
So it's a systemic process, you see.

52
00:05:32,247 --> 00:05:36,415
Now, some would say it happens naturally with the meditation, and I think that's true.

53
00:05:37,295 --> 00:05:48,435
But it's also good just to egg it along a bit, you know, just to keep sort of pushing it a wee bit and just to notice how sometimes our behavior upsets people.

54
00:05:48,937 --> 00:06:07,713
Of course, it might be their problem, not yours, but even so, it's that sort of ability to be sensitive to our relationships to people, which actually makes us more aware of intentions that we weren't perhaps particularly aware of.

55
00:06:09,637 --> 00:06:12,482
One obvious thing is when we want to help somebody.

56
00:06:13,153 --> 00:06:24,733
Whether we like it or not, there's always that sort of self-regard within it, a certain conceit that needs to be thanked, that needs to be acknowledged, that needs to be appreciated.

57
00:06:25,422 --> 00:06:31,975
And if the person whom you've just given all your money to doesn't say thank you, you feel very upset.

58
00:06:33,197 --> 00:06:36,163
It's a case of being aware of those things.

59
00:06:36,665 --> 00:06:42,877
And what our vipassana practice is telling us is not to get judgmental about it, it's just a conditioning.

60
00:06:44,019 --> 00:06:46,384
It's no good then berating ourselves.

61
00:06:46,617 --> 00:06:50,641
and judging ourselves as evil and things like that.

62
00:06:51,362 --> 00:06:58,427
It's a recognition of, that's a conditioning, and all I have to do is be aware of it and not empower it.

63
00:06:58,908 --> 00:06:59,850
It's as simple as that.

64
00:07:00,711 --> 00:07:09,418
And as we stop empowering those behaviors that we see are not ethical, not sila, they atrophy, they just die away.

65
00:07:09,439 --> 00:07:10,720
You don't have to do anything.

66
00:07:10,959 --> 00:07:15,644
That's the simplicity of the path.

67
00:07:25,867 --> 00:07:41,851
And then, of course, there's a sort of refinement of that until you're really talking about even small movements like making a noise when you're eating.

68
00:07:41,831 --> 00:07:52,769
It can get extremely fine about your behavior and about a certain delicacy, a certain courtesy.

69
00:07:53,630 --> 00:07:57,235
It moves towards a real sort of gentle way of being in the world.

70
00:07:59,038 --> 00:08:02,423
You know, sort of stabbing the plate with our knives and forks.

71
00:08:03,185 --> 00:08:04,507
Have compassion on the plate.

72
00:08:05,588 --> 00:08:06,591
Never meant any harm.

73
00:08:10,738 --> 00:08:13,062
Just the way we brush our teeth, gently.

74
00:08:14,303 --> 00:08:15,365
Just getting it over with.

75
00:08:16,365 --> 00:08:18,069
Things like that.

76
00:08:18,088 --> 00:08:23,334
So it moves us towards a real sort of refinement of behaviour.

77
00:08:26,158 --> 00:08:40,037
And that's really that process of sealer as a show of how wise and gentle, compassionate we can become.

78
00:08:41,586 --> 00:08:45,371
So Sila is really quite a basic teaching.

79
00:08:45,892 --> 00:09:02,092
And when Buddhism first began as a practice in the 60s and 70s and 80s, people were very afraid to talk about Sila, talk about behavior, especially sexual behavior because it was meant to be free and easy.

80
00:09:03,440 --> 00:09:07,783
But eventually it affects the whole way that you treat human beings.

81
00:09:08,865 --> 00:09:28,183
And you go back to that golden rule, you know, which began in that axial age with the Buddha, Lao Tzu, Socrates, Jeremiah, all these people, and it was just that one, you can reduce it all to that one phrase, you know, do unto others as you would have them do unto you.

82
00:09:30,385 --> 00:09:32,788
Not do unto others before they do unto you.

83
00:09:35,602 --> 00:09:39,595
Yeah, we have to abandon that.

84
00:09:39,615 --> 00:09:42,022
So I hope my words have been of some assistance.

85
00:09:42,302 --> 00:09:47,317
May you be liberated sooner rather than later.

